Bid 1S over 1D.  Most players have absorbed some of the lessons of Roth
and Kaplan but seem stuck with other sloppy ideas from the 1930s.
Doubling with this hand is a reflection of those sloppy ideas.  Even if
you insist on double followed by a new suit to show a good hand, this
ain't it.  Your D:QJx and C:Qx are perilously close to waste paper.

Having bid as you did, you have already shown every bit of value in your
hand if not more.  It is time to stop bidding.  Letting them play a
diamond partscore isn't such a bad thing here.  And your partner ought
not have as much as a 5/6 count with 3+ spades or 4+ clubs at this
point.  It doesn't take much, if you pass, for him to find a spark of
life over 2S. If he should bid 2S over 2D, it is not even clear that
that is a good thing: the opponents have not shown a hint that they have
found a fit.
